{"hits": {"hits": [{"created": "2024-08-29T05:58:33.846489+00:00", "modified": "2025-10-06T23:35:54.326632+00:00", "id": 13441690, "conceptrecid": "13441689", "doi": "10.5281/zenodo.13441690", "conceptdoi": "10.5281/zenodo.13441689", "doi_url": "https://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.13441690", "metadata": {"title": "Volume of foliage tents affects harem size in Cynopterus sphinx living in a fission-fusion society", "doi": "10.5281/zenodo.13441690", "publication_date": "2024", "description": "(Uploaded by Plazi for the Bat Literature Project) Cynopterus sphinx males construct dome-shaped tents in various foliage to form harems with females. It is generally assumed that C. sphinx follows resource-defence polygyny. However, a recent study suggests that these bats mate promiscuously and that forming harems confer no reproductive advantages for males. So, the selective forces maintaining male behaviours amid promiscuity still need to be better understood. Here, we studied the relationship between male body size, tent volume and harem size in a population of C. sphinx that roosts in drooping fronds of Borassus flabellifer. For the first time, we show that (1) male body size and tent volume or harem size are not correlated, suggesting that the benefits of tent construction to form harems may outweigh the costs of maintaining and defending the resource. And (2) tent volume positively correlates with the harem size in mating seasons, suggesting that males who use larger tents have a higher chance of attracting more females into their harems. Thus, females' preference to roost with males holding larger tents, even without direct reproductive benefits, might be the selective force maintaining male behaviours in C. sphinx.", "access_right": "restricted", "creators": [{"name": "Nagarajan-Radha, Venkatesh", "affiliation": null}, {"name": "Murugan, Subanithi-Purnima", "affiliation": null}, {"name": "Devaraj, Paramanantha Swami Doss", "affiliation": null}], "keywords": ["Biodiversity", "M